@gabbyscheyen Kay a lot of people ask me what exercises they can do to get rid of lower back fat... y'all you can't train away fat. There are no movements that help you lose back fat specifically. LOSING FAT COMES FROM A CALORIE DEFICIT. Aka, less calories then your body needs to function. You can achieve a deficit by burning extra calories through weight training, HIIT/LISS, or you can eat less calories to maintain a deficit. You can't just do an exercise and expect to lose fat from that area on your body... YOUğŸ‘ğŸ¼CAN'TğŸ‘ğŸ¼TARGETğŸ‘ğŸ¼FAT LOSS. You have to lose fat ALL OVER your body in order to lose "love handles". And I'm sorry to say but depending on genetics it may be hard for you to achieve that in a healthy way. We all genetically lose fat in different areas and at different rates. As women, we are BUILT to hold fat around our midsections. I hold fat in my back too. When I wear tight low rise pants you BET my fat hangs over (which is why I only wear high waisted leggings). But I pose in ways that makes me look best. I know my good angles in photos. Bottom line, you can't just train legs to lose fat on your thighs and you can't just train arms to lose fat on your arms. So you cant do back workouts to lose just fat on your back. You have to lose fat everywhere through a calorie deficit. A heartfelt & emotional throwback. This young man, at only 34, changed the entire direction of my life. Talk about impact and purpose. My late uncle Brian wasn't even a singer but was very educated and passionate when it came to opera. While he was alive it was his mission to instil his passion for opera in me. I casually sang some silly little song for him one day and he jumped up and said: Honey, you have a voice made for opera! Thus began the seasons tickets at the COC, buying me vocal scores, having me sing at his lavish parties, even emotionally coaching me on how to portray 'the tears in your voice, Tonia.' (Maria Callas was our go-to as the perfect example.) To quote him when I was a young singer, 'Tonia, you will hit your prime in your 40's. This is when you will come into your own.' And my god was he ever right. There's something about being in my 40's, things are unlocking and unfolding. You can't rush a fine wine, and you certainly can't rush the twists, turns, and detours of your life's journey because it is ALL part of what makes you, you, and contributes to your destiny. I am grateful for all of it. I got so present to this today in a coaching with Caren Levine who coaches between here in Miami and the MET opera, a rush! And knowing how much my uncle Brian LOVED to dance, I just know that he would be grooving to the new music I've found myself writing. Brian, you're with me, STILL, and I'll never stop working the gift God gave me and the desire you placed in my heart! ğŸ™ğŸ»â¤ï¸ #throwback #throwbackthursday #singer #songwriter #mentor #influence #anartistsjourney #blessed #uncle #opera #passion #toronto #torontolife #performer #wishescometrue #40  #femaledj #dj #mariacallas #coc #carenlevine #mannyparez #miami #musiciansofinstagram #photo #gifts #purpose #mastinkipp @mastinkipp #thedailylove #growingintograce

If you're going through hard shit right now, keep going! . . The human body, mind and spirit is so adaptive that it can grow and strengthen to ANY stimuli imposed upon it, and also weaken when nothing is imposed upon it. We grow when we're challenged, we grow when we're broken down, we grow when we're faced with obstacle, adversity, stress and pain. . . Your mind is no different than your muscles or bones, when it's challenged with an external force, it strengthens in order to meet that demand placed upon it. It is for that same reason that astronauts come back to earth with a lesser bone density because their bones aren't used in outer space to the degree that they are on earth due to the gravitational pull. In fact, it takes them 3-years to regain that same bone density.  We adapt to our environment, stress and challenge, or lack thereof. . . If you're faced with pain or challenge, embrace it because it's THAT pain or challenge that's the precursor and catalyst in making you one strong motherfucker. You may not realize it now, but when you look back at your life you'll realize that it was THAT event that caused you to grow, and if you're ever faced with that pain again it wouldn't inflict pain upon you. The key to growth is to never surrender to your circumstances no matter how bad they get, pain doesn't come to stay it comes to pass. Be thankful for the people and things that have hurt you, they're a blessing in disguise. @themindbuilder

I was tagged in this last night by the amazing Darla from @theartofrearranging (give her a follow you won't be disappointed) - I usually don't play along with these but this ones kinda fun so here goes !! 1- I am 28 year old mother to 3 boys 2- my husband is from Mexico and 50% of the time at home I talk with a fake Spanish accent. I can't help it 3- I'd like to have one more child before I'm 30ğŸ˜¬ 4- we have horses but I've never had a chance to learn to ride properly because I've always been pregnant 5- I am a total goof most of the time with a ridiculous sense of humour 6- I love music. It's one of the ways my soul speaks 7- I play guitar and piano but I'm a bit rusty  8- I'm very shy and uncomfortable in big groups 9- I prefer to keep my opinions to myself because ... well let's just leave it at that ;) 10- my mom is one of my best friends and favourite people to hang out with  11- when I still lived at home me and my dad had a best out of 101 games of cribbage over a few weeks - he won but it was close 12- I love being outside nature is my favourite 13- I love reading cheesy novels  14- I love watching cheesy movies  15- taking a bath is like a mini vacation for me and I do it often 16- aside from facebook and instagram I am not friends with anyone I went to school with ever 17- aside from my best friend that I met in grade 5 but she's basically just a sister  18- speaking of sisters I have 2 sisters and 2 brothers - second youngest out of 5  19- I love cooking and trying new recipes but my entire family is picky so I don't get to do it often 20- I adore being a stay at home mom in the traditional sense (don't get me wrong I totally respect working moms and major kudos to single moms out there killing it)  Wow if you read that thanks for reading!! Hi everyone!  This is Louis-Bernard St-Jean (@LBStJean) again for Petroff Gallery's artist #takeover! To follow Instagram's #throwbackthursday tradition, and with so much water pouring from the sky today, I would like to showcase a piece about aquatic life I painted back in 2014, the artwork titled 'Corail' [Coral]. Of unsettling depth and movement, the vibrant colors of coral reefs mark this artwork, in which the viewer is pulled into this underwater world where the beauty of the marine ecosystemâ€™s flora and fauna equals in fragility. Corail's painting style also presents a clear nod to one of my strongest art influences, Jean-Paul Riopelle's instantly recognizable palette knife works.  Many of my pieces from 2014-2015 are based on those techniques, as I was at the time studying and learning everything I could from them... And in parallel, also looking for any potentially working variations derived from these techniques that I could further develop and use profusely instead, experimenting on other pieces, seeing the results and evaluating their potential... which progressively led me to my own unique sculptural style!  The artwork Corail is currently on display in Petroff Gallery's front window, next to one of my most recent pieces, the artwork 'West Indies' (second photo)... Two paintings of the same size, made only three years apart!

YOUR TENSION HEADACHES MAY BE COMING FROM YOUR JAW! . For those of you that rarely get headaches unless you drink too much ğŸºğŸ·, consider yourself lucky ğŸ€ . Headaches (HA) are the most common disorders of the nervous system. There are 4 main types of headache disorders . ğŸ”¹MIGRAINES are more often found in women, 2-1 ratio. They are recurring and tend to be one-sided and pulsing and can last a few hours to a few days ğŸ”¹CLUSTER (CH) are more common in men, 6-1 ratio and consist of a recurring (several times a day) brief but intense and extremely sever HA ğŸ”¹MEDICATION-OVERUSE HA are caused by excessive use of medication to treat HA (ironic, I know) and are often persistent and worst in the mornings ğŸ”¹TENSION TYPE HEADACHES (TTH) can last a few hours or more and can feel like pressure or tightness sometimes in the front, side or back of the head . TTH In my clinical experience are commonly caused by the TMJ muscles. It's  regular thing for people that have had a blow to the head, a fall, been in a car accident or have high levels of stress to suffer from TTH . You can do the sequence of external or internal jaw techniques in my last post or if you have a similar pattern in the ğŸ“¸ use a tennis ball and lay on your side to knead out the trigger points. If you find a tender spot in the muscle, it may recreate your headache. This is okay and you should keep the ball on the "spot" until you feel it melt or the referral dissipate . . While full-body workouts seem to be increasing in popularity, body-part splits, most of which train a muscle group once a week, are still the predominate style of training for the vast majority of bodybuilders (~69%). [1] This is typically done using a 5-day body part split.  The following is research and reasons why higher training frequencies, in the form of full-body workouts and upper/lower splits, are superior for muscle and strength gains.  Studies that investigated the effects of training muscle groups between 1 to 3 days per week, on a volume-equated basis, showed higher frequencies of training were consistently superior to lower frequencies for increasing muscle mass. [2, 3]  Myofibrillar (muscle) protein synthesis (MPS, the process of muscle tissue growth and repair) last ~48 hours after resistance training [4] with other studies showing MPS levels returning to baseline after ~36 hours. [5] These levels also decrease as you advance as a lifter. [6] Note: There's one study that suggests MPS may not be correlated to hypertrophy [7] so letâ€™s make this a tentative point.  A meta-analysis found 2â€“3 sets resulted in 46% greater gains in hypertrophy than 1 set, where 4â€“6 sets only resulted in 13% greater gains than 2â€“3 sets. [8] As you can see, there are diminishing returns as you continue to do more sets on the same muscle group in a single session.  Greater overall muscle activation from full-body training enables your body is better utilize larger doses of post-workout dietary protein which further stimulate MPS. [9]  You can certainlyâ€‹ make great progress training muscle groups once a week.  But remember, it's not about what works, it's about works best. I believe that our understanding of precious time is displayed through our desire to take photos. Looking through photographs we took yesterday, or years ago makes us thoughtful. It takes us back to the moment it was taken - what we were thinking, how we were feeling, who was beside us. People shouldn't be judged when they want to take a picture of places they go, food they eat or friends they're with. It's our modern instinct. We should see it as a privilege that we have the resources to immortalize the moments we choose.

Back in 2010 I was managing a #footlocker when these shoes came out. I had first dibs at all releases, so there was no way I was going to pass these up. So on release day I had these put aside to buy them after my shift. During the day these were selling out quickly, we only had a size run. A guy came in with a desperate look on his face and his fingers crossed hoping we still had his size left. Unfortunately we did not. He told me he needed these and they were very special for him since it was the first Jordan is late mom bought him. That pulled at my heart strings, I went to stockroom and resurfaced with my pair for him to buy. He could not believe it he was so thrilled. Fast forward 7 years and karma came around full circle as a guy I do trades with gifted me these for the best steal I ever got. He told me he had many offers but knew how badly I wanted these, he took a loss to help me out. He's a young collector so he gives me hope that there's still passion, honour and respect in the game. #fouronekix

Grossman's Tavern has been "home of the blues" in Toronto for six decades. Grossman's opened as a cafeteria in 1948 and got a liquor licence a few years later. Over the years blues, R&B and jazz has mixed with the dive bar ambience. It's said that Dan Aykroyd would jam on his harmonica here in the '70s and often came to see the Downchild Blues Band, which was one of his inspirations for the Blues Brothers. Paul Shaffer played here years before his Letterman gig. Mondays are jam night and Grossman's boasts it never charges a cover to get in. A great Toronto live music venue whose worn sign is probably an apt reflection of its clientele.

In a world where we do everything in front of us with little side-to-side movement, the gluteus medius and minimis muscles that stabilize the pelvis and hip are vastly underused and usually weak. Weakness in these glutes is a HUGE contributor to hip problems, back pain and the cause of most running injuries in my experience.  In short, strengthening these lateral stabilizers is so important so anyone living the #desklife especially if you are active outside of the office. This exercise is fantastic because it is effective and can be done inconspicuously at the office while you work!  STEP 1: Sit or stand with exceptional posture as discussed previously STEP 2: Loop a Theraband around the knees, shin, ankle or forefoot STEP 3: Brace your core Step 4: Using the glutes on the side of your hips, draw the feet and knees apart from each other without allowing any sideways bending at the knee STEP 5: Hold for 60 seconds or as long as possible STEP 6: Repeat for 3 or more sets STEP 7: Progress this exercise by placing the resistance band father and farther towards the toes. IMPORTANT â€“ For knee safety, do not progress the looping of the Theraband close to the toes unless you can maintain a straight angle between the hips, knees and ankles. FITS Hold for 10-60 seconds. Enjoying Japan cherry blossom at Fushimi Momoyama Jyo (Castle), Kyoto. This is one of the most beautiful secret place to see and enjoy cherry blossom. Definitely no crowded and you surety will enjoy a wonderful serene moment here, because all the visitors here are local Japanese, almost no tourist will come to here. There are lots of cherry trees in different colors in this castle.  Fushimi Momoyamajyo is one of the eleven wards in the city of Kyoto, in Kyoto Prefecture, Japan. Fushimi Castle, originally built by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, with its rebuilt towers and gold-lined tea-room; and the Teradaya, an inn at which Sakamoto RyÅma was attacked and injured about a year before his assassination. Also of note is the GokÅgu shrine, which houses a stone used in the construction of Fushimi Castle. The water in the shrine is particularly famous and it is recorded as one of Japan's 100 best clear water spots. Kyoto, Japan.

Dinner tonight is picture perfect, taking inspiration from beautiful plates prepared by some of my favourite chefs... Although it may appear to be 'fancy', I'm here to tell you it's much simpler than that and possible for the untrained cook! On the menu tonight (between essay writing and exam studying) Asparagus wrapped in Balsamic and Garlic marinated Steak Rounds on a bed of Rosemary Cinnamon Mashed Potatoes, seasoned and embellished with Chili Flakes and Extra Balsamic Vinaigrette, Salt and Pepper. For the Steaks I simply dressed them in Vinaigrette and lightly dusted them with Curry Powder and laid them flat to prepare them for the Veggies. Next, add my chopped Garlic Cloves and Boiled Asparagus to each round and ROLL! Kebab skewers did the trick in holding them together until they finished in the oven (230 C for about 15 minutes - this will depend on your oven!). Housing affordability measures coming 'very soon,' says Ontario's Wynne  BNN-TORONTO -- Ontario Premier Kathleen Wynne says her government will introduce a package of housing affordability measures "very soon" that she believes will have a swift impact on the hot Toronto-area housing market.  When asked if the package would include measures that may have a swift cooling effect on the market, such as a tax on foreign buyers or real estate speculators, Wynne says there's a need for action that will have an impact "fairly quickly." The premier wouldn't provide any details on the package, but says her Liberal government recognizes the complexity of the market and will be judicious in its approach.  Meanwhile, Ontario Progressive Conservative Leader Patrick Brown is calling for longer-term measures to address housing supply shortage. This fast, easy and delicious Asparagus Stuffed Chicken Breast recipe is a perfect meal for your weeknight dinner and it requires only 4-ingredient. . Ingredients: . 4 large chicken breasts 1 tbsp lemon zest salt and pepper 12 asparagus stalks, trimmed 3 slices mozzarella cheese 1 tsp garlic powder 1 tsp paprika 1 tbsp olive oil . Instructions: . Preheat oven to 425 degrees F. Cut the chicken breast in half, length-wise. Please do not cut all the way though. You need to create a pocket into each chicken breast. Season the inside of the chicken breast with lemon zest, salt and pepper. Place chicken on work surface and lay the mozzarella cheese and 3 asparagus inside of each chicken breast and fold over, enclosing the filling. In a small bowl mix together salt, pepper garlic powder and paprika. Then season the outside of the chicken breast with this spice mixture. Heat a large and oven safe skillet over medium-high heat. Add the olive oil. Cook the chicken for 3 to 5 minutes each side and until the chicken is golden brown on top. Place the chicken in the oven. Bake for 20 minutes. Make sure the chicken reaches the internal temperature of 165 degrees. . . . #feedfeed #cookinglight #toronto #torontofood #torontoeats #yahoofood #huffpostfood #foodgawker #food #buzzfeedfood #thefeedfeed #foodblogger #foodporn #cooking #foodie #food52 #torontoblogger #foodstagram #healthyeats #saveurmag #buzzfeast #instafood #recipe healthyrecipes #healthyeating #fbcigers

Our last artist chat of the LAND exhibition! Featuring artists:  Shawntol Drakes @melanoiremedia, Alleben Purugganan @alleben, and Aimee Wu @aimeetwu  As part of an ongoing series, we invite Own the Walls' exhibiting artists & friends to participate in an intimate community discussion on their artwork and surrounding themes. . . *When: Thursday, April 13. Doors open 6PM, Discussion 7PM *Where: 4th floor, 215 Spadina Ave. *Kid-friendly - Free admission - Light snacks and drinks will be served* . . *Accessibility info*  215 Spadina Ave's front entrance is barrier-free and there is an elevator to the 4th floor. There are 2 gendered washrooms, and 1 gender-neutral wheelchair accessible washroom but no automated buttons. This is a dog-friendly shared workspace. Please avoid wearing scented materials. *If you require childcare or mobility assistance please let us know and we will strive to find a designated volunteer - contact ownthewalls.to@gmail.com  FEATURED ARTISTS:  Shawntol Drakes is an Afro-Guyanese mixed media artist from Toronto, ON. Her artwork focuses on showcasing the multi dimensional aspects of the experience of folks within the African Diaspora. Through photography, graphic design and writing, Shawntol tells stories of the multiplicities of the Black experience.  Alleben Tallo Purugganan is a community-based cultural worker and arts educator. She has previously worked on installations produced in collaboration with Filipino youth and caregivers as part of the Maleta Project in Gallery 44 and for Nuit Blanche in 2012.  Aimee Wu is a 21-year-old Chinese-Canadian creator. She loves to DIY and create works from unconventional mediums. Her art seeks to examine our personal attachments to the things around us, and the socio-spatial contexts to which the objects are transformed into iconographical symbols. Aimee is a proud owner of a golden retriever, and is an avid knitter. She is committed to further uncovering, uplifting and telling the stories oftentimes suppressed or forgotten.

"When I was approached to answer this question I truly didn't know how to answer the question. Thought about it, and thought about it some more. The only way I can change the world is by impacting good people in my life and hoping for a ripple effect one by one. I'm here to open up and say that I'm the individual many people told was never going to do anything in life. Never go to university, never graduate, never get a full time job, never know how to live on my own. Nothing but make bad choices. Each day in and day out I'm a living example that no matter what odds are against you that you are always in full control of your own future and no matter what life throws at you, you always have a choice to make, and that will determine what life and lifestyle you live. Life is determined by the short term decisions you make. We're only given one life and if I can speak to my friends and be the light for them at the end of the tunnel, then one day when another friend is down they can be their light and thus the ripple effect can begin.  So again to answer the question; "How would you like to change the world?" my answer is this: I wake up each day and simply be better then who I was the previous day. No bullshit, no shortcuts, no hand outs. If you want something in life and that specific thing can be different for everyone, lock in on it and don't stop until you've reached your goal and then when you have made it or reached your goal, spread your success with good people and show them there's always a way, even through tragedy. Thanks Michael GP for giving me the opportunity to open up to the world. âœŒğŸ½" â€¢ â€¢ â€¢ How would you like to #changetheworld?
